      "writtenOn": "2018-10-09T03:24:28Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I\u0027m wondering if we can prevent misuse in more effective way. Below let\u0027s consider chrome.LoggedInPre as an example.\n\nIIUC misuse we want to catch with this function is that test functions call chrome.LoggedIn() directly to get a precondition object not delcared in AddTest.\n\nHow about just unexporting chrome.LoggedInPre, i.e. naming it chrome.loggedInPre, and returning it as Precondition? That is:\n\n\n \u003d\u003d\u003d chrome.go\n\n type loggedInPre struct { ... }\n\n var aLoggedInPre *loggedInPre \u003d \u0026loggedInPre{...}\n\n func LoggedInPre() Precondition {\n   return aLoggedInPre\n }\n\n\n \u003d\u003d\u003d chrome_login.go\n\n func init() {\n   testing.AddTest(\u0026testing.Test{\n     ...\n     Pre: chrome.LoggedInPre(),\n   })\n }\n\n func ChromeLogin(ctx context.Context, s *testing.State) {\n   cr :\u003d chrome.UseLoggedInPre(s)\n }\n\n\nPros of this approach might be:\n- Test functions can\u0027t do anything useful by calling chrome.LoggedInPre() directly because it returns just Precondition interface and real struct is unexported. It eliminates the need to RunningTest function too.\n- Test functions can\u0027t construct loggedInPre struct directly.\n- Test functiosn don\u0027t need to (and can\u0027t) do type assertion of s.Pre(), which is more intuitive.\n\nWDYT?",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 197,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 203,
        "endChar": 1
      },
      "revId": "0b35769fdc3c43073742e354c80af83ac3914ccf",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "03da5e27_2bb16b7d",
        "filename": "src/chromiumos/tast/testing/state.go",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 203,
      "author": {
        "id": 1000042
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-10-09T05:22:30Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "i\u0027m reluctant to use an interface like this, because i feel like it may not scale well to preconditions that offer additional functionality (e.g. my proof-of-concept arc-booted precondition has accessors for both *Chrome and *ARC), and it could get complicated if a package provides multiple preconditions (which i think may be the case in the future). i\u0027d rather group all of the precondition\u0027s functionality (at least from a test\u0027s perspective) into a single type.\n\nif we took this approach, i think we\u0027d need to offer a method like State.Pre that UseLoggedInPre would call to get a Precondition from State that it can convert to a *loggedInPre, right? we may still need to guard against tests calling that method and invoking the precondition\u0027s Prepare and Close methods directly.\n\ni think the main requirements here are:\n- expose a common interface to testing.Test.Run (and ideally nothing to code outside of the testing package) with Prepare, Close, Timeout, and String methods\n- expose a different set of precondition-specific functions to tests that use the precondition\n\ni can think of convoluted ways to accomplish this, but they all seem to sacrifice the property that the object that the test author registers in Test.Pre is directly connected to the type of the object that the test author later uses in their test. i think that that\u0027s a somewhat important property to have for making the code easier for test authors to understand.\n\nso i still don\u0027t have any good solutions here. what i\u0027d really like to do is make Prepare/Close/Timeout/String private, in the sense that they\u0027re only callable by the testing package, but i don\u0027t think that that\u0027s possible to do in go.",
      "parentUuid": "734b1561_5e2c85fc",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 197,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 203,
        "endChar": 1
      },
      "revId": "0b35769fdc3c43073742e354c80af83ac3914ccf",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
